Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup that tries to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company that takes its origins from Berners-Lee's open source platform.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and what people can access and what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked about the fact that the intention behind Inrupt is to "dominate the world".
"We have to do it now," he said about the startup.
"It's a historic moment."
The app uses Solid technology to allow people to create their own "online personal data store" or a POD.
It can include lists of contacts, things to do, calendars, music libraries and other personal and professional instruments.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available on one browser and at the same time.
The uniqueness of the online personal data store is that it is entirely at the discretion of the user who can have access to what type of information.
The company calls it "personal power through data."
The idea for Inrupt, according to John Bruce, CEO of the company, is to provide adequate resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to all.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased from IBM, some developers in the staff hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
As of this week, technology programmers around the world will be able to give life to their decentralized apps using the tools available on Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team will not say to "Facebook and Google whether or not to introduce a complete change where their business models are completely discarded from one day to another.
"We're not asking their permission."
In a post on the Medium published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "Inrupt's mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps to protect the integrity and quality of the new web built from Solid".
In 1994 Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months Berners-Lee has represented an influential voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Also after the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the Founder and Director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I'm incredibly optimistic about this new era of the web," said Berners-Lee.
