Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt "lower" because of sexuality
The Olympic swimmer Tom Daley says he's grown feeling less than anyone because of his sexuality - but this has given him the motivation to succeed.
The 24 year old said he didn't realize until he got to high school, that "not everyone is like me."
Speaking in the first episode of Desert Island Discs on Radio 4, presented by Lauren Laverne, he said he had made his voice heard about gay rights to give others "hope".
He also stated that he had become a parent so that he would have less interest in winning the Olympics.
The usual presenter of the old-time program, Kirsty Young, took a series of free months for illness.
Presenting himself as an outcast in Laverne's first program, Daley said he felt "less than" anyone else as he grew up because "it was socially unacceptable that he liked both boys and girls."
He said, "Today, the feeling of feeling less than, and feeling different, were the things that really gave me strength and energy to succeed."
He wanted to try to be "something," he said, so that no one would be disappointed if they had discovered his sexuality by chance.
The bronze medal twice at the Olympics has become a high-profile LGBT activist and has used his face in this year's Australian Commonwealth Games to appeal to several countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said that he had made his voice heard because he felt lucky to be able to live openly without consequences and wanted to give others "hope."
The three times world champion said that the fact that he fell in love with a man - the American director Dustin Lance Black, who met in 2013 - "I was surprised".
Daley married Oscar's winner, who was 20 years older than him last year, but said the age difference was never a problem.
"When she spent so much of it in her young age" - she went to her first Olympics when she was 14 years old and her father died of cancer three years later - she said it was hard to find someone of the same age who had experienced similar heights and lows.
The two became parents in June, of a child named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley said his "whole perspective" has changed.
"If you asked me last year, it was all about the fact that 'I had to win a gold medal'," he said.
"You know, there are things more important than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie."
His son bears the same name as his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after he was diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father had not accepted the fact that he was going to die and that one of the last things he asked was if they already had tickets to London 2012 - because he wanted to be in front of the line.
"I couldn't say to him, 'You won't be around here so you can be in the front row, Dad," he said.
"I was holding my hand when he stopped breathing and until he actually stopped and died, I had not yet realized that he was not invincible," he said.
The following year Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics, winning the bronze.
"I only knew it was what I had dreamed of all my life - swimming in front of a home audience in the Olympic Games, there was no better feeling," he said.
This also inspired the choice of his first song - Heather Small's Proud - which had a special meaning for him in the preparation for the Olympics and still makes him come the goose skin.
