The new German military ship has been postponed again
According to local media, the last German military fleet was to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the old military ships of the cold war times, but there will not be at least until next year due to defective systems and a burden of costs.
The commission of Rheinland-Pfalz, the admiral ship of the new mills of the Baden-Württemberg class, was postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, which mentions a military spokesman.
The ship was supposed to join the military navy in 2014, but worrying issues following delivery tormented the fate of the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Württemberg class ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the old ships of the Bremen class.
They will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-air and anti-aircraft missiles as well as some hidden technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signals.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, in fact it should be possible to use the new mills up to two years away from national ports.
However, the continuing delays mean that the innovative warships, which are said to allow Germany to project its overseas power, will already become obsolete when they come into service, notes the Die Zeit.
The unfortunate F-125 fregate made news last year, when the German Navy officially refused to commission the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy returned a ship to the manufacturer after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but the German media noted a number of crucial "defect software and hardware" that made the ship useless if used in a combat mission.
The shortcomings in the software were particularly important as the vessels of the Baden-Württemberg class will be managed by a crew of about 120 sailors, just half of the staff of the oldest ships of the Bremen class.
Furthermore, it has emerged that the ship weighs significantly too much, and this reduces its performance and limits the military Navy's ability to add future updates.
Rheinland-Pfalz, of 7,000 tonnes, is believed to be twice as heavy as the ships of similar classes used by the Germans in the Second World War.
Apart from the defective hardware, the cost of the entire project (including crew training) is becoming an important issue.
It seems that it has reached the 3.1 billion euros (3.6 billion dollars) from the initial 2.2 billion euros.
The problems involved in the new sinks become of particular importance in the light of recent alarms concerning the reduction of German naval power.
At the beginning of the year, Hans-Peter Bartels, Parliamentary Commissioner for the Armed Forces, admitted that the military Navy actually "loads ships capable of being used".
The official said that the issue has worsened considerably over time, since the old unarmed ships have not been replaced by new ships.
His regret is that none of the baden-Württemberg class frigates were able to join the Navy.
The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
New research carried out in a Scottish Highland estate is aimed at revealing how bats use sight to get food.
It is hoped that discoveries can shed light on the behaviour of the only existing flying mammals and guide future protection activities.
The study of the National Trust for Scotland scientists will follow common and soprano bats, as well as brown earrings and Daubenton bats at the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to track the activities of bats during the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations using portable detectors.
The analysis of the sounds recorded by an expert will determine the frequency of callbacks of bats and the manner in which each species behaves.
They will then produce a map of habitat and a report to create a detailed picture on the scale of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a consultant for nature protection for the NTS, hopes that the results can reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of grasslands, and how best to maintain the forests for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom declined significantly in the last century.
The bats are at risk because of the construction and development work that affects trespolies and damage habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a threat, as well as moschicide paper and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks of domestic cats.
The bats aren't really blind.
However, due to their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique to detect insects and obstacles on their path.
The NTS, responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
Ten qualified experts regularly conduct investigations, inspect trespolies and sometimes carry out rescues.
The organization has even established the first reserve of Scotland intended solely for bats in the estate of Three, in the region of Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of the ten species of bats of Scotland.
The estate manager, David Thompson, says the property is the ideal territory.
"Here in Three we have a vast area for bats," he said.
"We have the ancient buildings, many secular trees and a good habitat.
But there's a lot about bats that we don't know yet, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us understand more about their need for growth."
It stresses the importance of controlling bats before conducting maintenance within the properties as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of a single maternal trespolus can kill up to 400 females and small, perhaps sweeping away a whole local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, disturb them, disturb them or destroy their trenches.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish head of Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
He said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don't know how their populations are passing through."
