Foreign buyers will be subject to higher stamp taxes for buying property in the United Kingdom
Foreign buyers will be subject to higher stamp taxes for buying property in the UK and the additional cash flow will be used to help homeless people, according to the new plans of the workers
The maneuver will neutralize the success of Corbyn's initiative to attract young voters
The increase in stamp tax will be applied to taxpayers who do not pay taxes in the United Kingdom
The Treasury Ministry plans to collect up to £120 million a year to help homeless people
Foreign buyers will be subject to higher stamp taxes for buying property in the UK and the additional cash flow will be used to help homeless people, it will announce today Theresa May.
The maneuver will be seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn's initiative to attract young voters with the promise of providing accommodation at a more affordable price and higher income.
The increase in the stamp tax will be applied to individuals and companies that do not pay taxes in the UK, and the additional resources will be in support of the Government's initiative to combat the homeless.
The surcharge, which is added to the current stamp tax, including the high levels introduced two years ago on the second houses and on the buildings buy to lets (sold for rent), could be more than 3%.
The Treasury Ministry expects the maneuver to collect up to £120 million a year.
An estimated 13% of the new constructions in London are purchased by non-resident citizens in the UK, increasing prices and making it difficult for buyers of a first home to enter the real estate market.
Many of the richest areas in the country, especially in the capital, have become "ghost city" because of the large number of foreign buyers who spend most of the time outside the state.
The new policy comes a few weeks after Boris Johnson had requested a cut on the stamp tax to help the younger ones with the purchase of the first house.
He accused the large construction companies of keeping the prices of the real estate up by gaining land without using them and encouraged Prime Minister May to renounce the affordable housing allowances to fix the British "real estate disgrace".
Mr Corbyn announced an exciting series of proposals for reform of the housing market, including controls on rents and the elimination of unpunished expenses.
He also wants to give the board more powers over the construction of new buildings.
Prime Minister May said: "Last year I said that I would be committed to restoring the British dream, that is, life should be better for the new generations.
And that means restoring the real estate market.
Britain will always be open to people who want to live, work and build a life here.
However, it would not be fair if buying a house was equally easy for people who do not live in the United Kingdom and for foreign companies, as it is for resident British workers.
For so many people the dream of owning a house has become too distant and the dignity of the homeless remains a reality."
