Nickel extraction is also an important activity in the province, but it is mostly concentrated in Morrowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit several times by tsunamis in the last 100 years, according to the Disaster Mitigation Agency of Indonesia.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
Another tsunami hit the western area of Donggala in 1996 killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the seismic area called the Pacific fire belt and is often affected by earthquakes.
Here are some of the strongest earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: On 26 December a very strong earthquake on the west coast of Aceh province north of Sumatra caused a tsunami that struck 14 countries killing, along the Indian Ocean coast, 226,000 people, of which more than half of Aceh.
2005: a series of strong earthquakes struck the western coast of Sumatra between the end of March and the beginning of April.
