Red tide upgrade: concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
Florida's latest report Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in red tide concentration in parts of Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, conditions of flowering at cheeks, which suggest a decrease of the concentration, are evident in the areas of the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier.
The red tide flowering extends for about 130 miles from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The collages are about 10 miles away from Hillsborough County but in less areas than last week.
The red tide was also observed in the county of Pasco.
Last week an average concentration was reported in the county of Pinellas or off its coast, a low-to-high concentration off Hillsborough County, from a bottom concentration to a high concentration in the county of Manatee, from a bottom concentration to a high concentration in the county of Sarasota or off its coast, from a bottom concentration to an average concentration in Charlotte County, from a bottom concentration to a high concentration in the county of Lee or off its coast and a low concentration on the county of Collier.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
While last week no cases were reported in northwestern Florida.
